english:
  title: Admiring Spring at a Pastoral Pavilion in Late March
  author: Lim Yu-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A visitor seeks the flowers and climbs to an ancient terrace—
    Saint Yu's delight.
    Spring wind freely opens ten thousand blossoms—
    Everlasting Virtue's song.
    One branch holds firm while a thousand burst forth—
    Yang Pan's wonder.
    March wanes, and April rushes near—
    Choney Chi's lament.
    The mountain's hue shows finest after rain clears—
    Zheng Gu's observation.
    The stream's voice follows close within my drunken joy—
    Zhao De-lin's discovery.
    How lovely—all these images of spring remain worth savoring—
    Yin Shun's contentment.
    Do not learn Wang Ziye's way, whose passion left him turning back—
    Zhu Fu's counsel.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is composed of eight couplets, each attributed to different poets whose names appear in parentheses in the original. This form represents a collaborative literary game popular among East Asian literati.
    - Wang Ziye (王子猷) was a famous Jin Dynasty figure known for abandoning his journey when his excitement faded, becoming proverbial for ephemeral enthusiasm.
